I’ve been in Athens for two whole months now. Wow—how time flies.

I think it’s important to regularly assess how things are going with language learning. I try to do a small mental check each day — what went well, what didn’t, and what I should do next. But I also want to step back once a month and take a broader look to make sure I’m staying on track.

## What has worked well

A few things have been especially helpful so far.

### Flashcards without translation

Making flashcards using only Greek, with no English, has been very effective. It forces me to connect directly with the language instead of relying on translation.

### Using ChatGPT as a teacher

I’ve been using ChatGPT a lot as a kind of language tutor. Here are some of the ways it has helped me:

1. I upload screenshots from Duolingo and ask for a lesson based on those.
2. I wrote a couple of paragraphs about my family, took a picture, and uploaded it for correction.
3. I ask for sentences to translate. At first I typed my answers on my phone, but the autocorrect suggestions were short-circuiting my learning. Now I write the sentences in a notebook, take a picture, and upload them.
4. I ask for quizzes to test my understanding.

### Creating my own tools

I also created a small app to help me practice Greek cases. That has been very useful for focused practice.

### Listening with support

At church, I used Google Translate in conversation mode to follow the sermon. I could listen to the Greek and see the translation at the same time, which was very helpful.

## What has not gone well

There is one main weakness in my learning so far.

I have not made myself get out and talk to people.

I’ve spent much more time on **input** — mostly reading, and a bit of listening — and not nearly enough on **output**, especially speaking.

## What I need to keep doing

There are some things that are working well and that I need to continue.

1. I want to keep using my flashcards. My goal is not just to recognize the word, but to **say a sentence using it**. This is still difficult with many words, which means I need to keep practicing.

2. I also want to keep asking ChatGPT for lessons. That has been one of the most helpful parts of my learning so far.

## What I want to do differently in month 3

1. The biggest change I need to make is to **start speaking more with real people**.
   I need to be more intentional about getting out into the community — whether that’s at the local fruit market or in small shops. I don’t see my neighbors very often, so I need to look for other opportunities.
   This is my main weakness right now, and I need to make a real effort to change it.

2. I also want to start learning some songs in Greek. At church, there are a few songs that we have already sung more than once. I’d like to find out which songs are most common and begin learning them.
   Songs are a great way to learn vocabulary and internalize patterns in the language.

## Looking ahead

Overall, I’m encouraged. I am learning, and I can see progress.

But if I want to move forward, I need to shift the balance — less passive learning, and more active use.

Month three will be about **speaking more, using what I know, and stepping out of my comfort zone a bit more**.
